Analyst Note: Introducing Unit - Bringing Spot BTC to Hyperliquid

Sunny Shi

Feb 14, 2025 ⋅  3 min read

Introduction

Until now, spot trading on Hyperliquid has been confined to a limited selection of Hyperliquid native assets. Today, Unit, a third-party team building on Hyperliquid’s native L1, has launched a mechanism that will enable direct spot BTC trading on Hyperliquid’s orderbook. This marks the first step in a broader expansion, with the underlying infrastructure designed to facilitate liquid, onchain trading for any asset in the future, including other majors, top alts, and RWAs.

Unit aims to be the asset tokenization layer for Hyperliquid, designed to facilitate seamless deposits and withdrawals of major crypto assets like BTC, ETH, and SOL. Unlike traditional BTC trading solutions that rely on custodians, Unit ensures users maintain full control over their assets while trading on Hyperliquid’s L1.

How Unit Works

At the core of Unit’s design is its Guardian Network, a distributed system of independent operators that verify transactions and enable trust-minimized cross-chain transfers. Unit’s Multi-Party Computation (MPC) Threshold Signature Scheme (TSS) ensures that assets remain self-custodied while being tradable on Hyperliquid.

The process is simple:

  1. Deposits – Users send BTC, ETH, or SOL from their wallets or exchange accounts to an address generated by Unit’s MPC Guardian Network. Once confirmed on the native chain, the corresponding assets become available on Hyperliquid for trading.
  2. Trading – These assets can be used on Hyperliquid’s spot orderbook and can potentially be unlocked as margin and collateral for the perp DEX and other HyperEVM DeFi integrations.
  3. Withdrawals – Users can withdraw assets by entering their destination address, at which point Unit generates and broadcasts the corresponding transaction to the native blockchain.

WBTC and other alternative BTC tokens typically require users to trust a central custodian.

Unit eliminates these issues by:

  • Preserving Self-Custody – Assets never leave users’ control, reducing counterparty risk.
  • Improving Efficiency – Deposits and withdrawals are processed with minimal friction, abstracting away technical complexities for the end user. For most, trading BTC on Hyperliquid will be as simple as trading HYPE.
  • Enhancing Security – The Guardian Network uses blockchain indexers and requires cryptographic verification at every step.

Looking forward, Unit’s Guardian Network will act as an indexing interface which can allow any crypto asset to be deposited, traded, and withdrawn from Hyperliquid’s orderbook. For traders, these additions will essentially act as token “listings”, slowly growing the tradeable universe on Hyperliquid.

Why This Matters

For Bitcoin specifically, Unit represents a trust-minimized and self-custodial method for integrating BTC into DeFi outside of Bitcoin mainnet. It removes the need for centralized intermediaries while maintaining a user experience as simple as a standard blockchain transfer.

For Hyperliquid, Unit moves the protocol one step closer to being a complete onchain financial ecosystem and the premiere trading chain in crypto. Hyperliquid traders can access CEX-like execution and gain exposure to the entire crypto asset class through perps and/or spot holdings. The L1 now also has additional onramp routes, allowing users to seamlessly transfer native BTC to USDC that is usable within Hyperliquid’s orderbook.

By working with top market makers on Hyperliquid, Unit can bring deep liquidity and tighter spreads using Hyperliquid’s native Central-Limit Order Book (CLOB) and performant infrastructure, a superior setup when compared to AMM DEXs on general-purpose L1s. The protocol also offers lower fees than typical trading interfaces and CEXs. We would not be surprised to see Hyperliquid become the best execution environment to trade BTC onchain in the near future.

For a more in-depth breakdown of what this means for Hyperliquid, read our prior report on the topic here.
